If you're not using Sentry or any other error tracking service, it's still important to handle errors gracefully in your application. Logging the error is a good practice as it helps you diagnose issues later. Depending on the context of your application, you might also want to provide some user feedback or take corrective actions.

Here's a basic example of how you might handle errors in a Node.js application using plain logging:

```javascript
const fs = require('fs');

function readFile(filePath) {
  try {
    const data = fs.readFileSync(filePath, 'utf8');
    console.log(data);
  } catch (error) {
    // Log the error
    console.error('Error reading file:', error.message);

    // Optionally, you can log the stack trace for more detailed debugging
    console.error(error.stack);

    // Provide user feedback or take corrective action
    // For example, you might want to return a default value or notify the user
    return null;
  }
}

// Example usage
const filePath = 'path/to/your/file.txt';
const fileContent = readFile(filePath);

if (fileContent === null) {
  console.log('Failed to read the file. Please check the file path and try again.');
} else {
  console.log('File content:', fileContent);
}
```

In this example:
1. The `readFile` function attempts to read a file synchronously.
2. If an error occurs, it logs the error message and stack trace.
3. It returns `null` to indicate that the operation failed.
4. The calling code checks if the result is `null` and provides appropriate feedback to the user.

You can adapt this pattern to fit your specific needs. For instance, if you're working with an Express.js application, you might want to send an appropriate HTTP response instead of just logging the error.

Here's an example for an Express.js route handler:

```javascript
const express = require('express');
const app = express();

app.get('/read-file', (req, res) => {
  const filePath = 'path/to/your/file.txt';

  try {
    const data = fs.readFileSync(filePath, 'utf8');
    res.send(data);
  } catch (error) {
    // Log the error
    console.error('Error reading file:', error.message);
    console.error(error.stack);

    // Send an appropriate HTTP response
    res.status(500).send('Internal Server Error: Unable to read the file.');
  }
});

app.listen(3000, () => {
  console.log('Server is running on port 3000');
});
```

In this Express.js example:
1. The route handler attempts to read a file.
2. If an error occurs, it logs the error and sends a 500 Internal Server Error response to the client.

By handling errors gracefully and providing appropriate feedback, you can improve the robustness and user experience of your application.
